O:9:"MagpieRSS":21:{s:6:"parser";i:0;s:12:"current_item";a:0:{}s:5:"items";a:10:{i:0;a:10:{s:5:"title";s:35:"CAW boss announces early retirement";s:8:"category";s:9:"CAWUnions";s:2:"dc";a:1:{s:7:"creator";s:13:"Peter Johnson";}s:7:"pubdate";s:31:"Wed, 09 Jul 2008 10:39:26 +0000";s:4:"link";s:78:"http://www.autonorth.ca/home/2008/7/9/caw-boss-announces-early-retirement.html";s:4:"guid";s:20:"75787:650998:1977049";s:11:"description";s:1318:"<p><span class="full-image-float-left"><img src="http://www.autonorth.ca/storage/CAW_logo.gif" alt="CAW_logo.gif" title="CAW_logo.gif"/></span>In a move that surprised everyone, Buzz Hargrove announced yesterday that he will be retire early as president of the Canadian Auto Workers union. He will retire no later than September 15th. Up until yesterday he was expected to hang on until March of ?09.</p>

<p>Hargrove has been the head of the <span class="caps">CAW </span>since 1992. In his tenure he fought tirelessly to ensure that union members got a fair shake. Regardless of whether you like or dislike him, you can't argue that he did his job well. </p>

<p>Senior officials at the <span class="caps">CAW </span>endorsed Ken Lewenza as his successor. Two other candidates in the running withdrew from the race leaving Lewenza as the inevitable president.</p>

<p>Is it worth the stress? The president of the 250,000 member Canadian Auto Workers union earns $150,700 annually. </p>

<p>The <span class="caps">CAW </span>is heading into a difficult period with more and more manufacturing jobs being wiped out across the country due to the weakening economy and high Canadian dollar.</p>

<p>Will Lewenza meet up to the high standards of Hargrove? Only time will tell. </p>

<p>[Source: Reportonbusiness.com]</p>
