";s:14:"date_timestamp";i:1215513300;}i:6;a:10:{s:5:"title";s:33:"Chrysler Canada to offer free gas";s:8:"category";s:8:"Chrysler";s:2:"dc";a:1:{s:7:"creator";s:14:"Karen McGinnis";}s:7:"pubdate";s:31:"Mon, 07 Jul 2008 19:51:36 +0000";s:4:"link";s:76:"http://www.autonorth.ca/home/2008/7/7/chrysler-canada-to-offer-free-gas.html";s:4:"guid";s:20:"75787:650998:1972233";s:11:"description";s:1162:"<p><span class="full-image-float-left"><img src="http://www.autonorth.ca/storage/ChryslerLightLogo.jpg?__SQUARESPACE_CACHEVERSION=1215460951215" alt="ChryslerLightLogo.jpg" title="ChryslerLightLogo.jpg"/></span>Canadian automakers have begun following our neighbours to the south in using free gasoline as incentive to get customers into their dealerships.  It?s a strategy they hope will reel in frustrated consumers and boost slumping sales.</p>

<p>Chrysler Canada has therefore announced that it will begin offering free gas for six months on almost all its vehicles, saying the move would shake up the market when combined with price cuts.  Currently, in the United States the automaker is offering buyers a locked-in gas price of US $2.99 a gallon for three years.</p>

<p>Similarly, the other domestic automakers ? Ford and General Motors - have comparable systems in place.  For instance, Ford Motor Co. does not have an incentive linked to gasoline prices in Canada but prefers to offer a direct discount on its vehicles.  General Motors of Canada is offering a preferred-price gas savings card worth up to 40 cents a litre on 2,500 litres of fuel.</p>
";s:3:"wfw";a:1:{s:10:"commentrss";s:59:"http://www.autonorth.ca/home/rss-comments-entry-1972233.xml";}s:7:"summary";s:1162:"<p><span class="full-image-float-left"><img src="http://www.autonorth.ca/storage/ChryslerLightLogo.jpg?__SQUARESPACE_CACHEVERSION=1215460951215" alt="ChryslerLightLogo.jpg" title="ChryslerLightLogo.jpg"/></span>Canadian automakers have begun following our neighbours to the south in using free gasoline as incentive to get customers into their dealerships.  It?s a strategy they hope will reel in frustrated consumers and boost slumping sales.</p>

<p>Chrysler Canada has therefore announced that it will begin offering free gas for six months on almost all its vehicles, saying the move would shake up the market when combined with price cuts.  Currently, in the United States the automaker is offering buyers a locked-in gas price of US $2.99 a gallon for three years.</p>

<p>Similarly, the other domestic automakers ? Ford and General Motors - have comparable systems in place.  For instance, Ford Motor Co. does not have an incentive linked to gasoline prices in Canada but prefers to offer a direct discount on its vehicles.  General Motors of Canada is offering a preferred-price gas savings card worth up to 40 cents a litre on 2,500 litres of fuel.</p>
";s:14:"date_timestamp";i:1215460296;}i:7;a:10:{s:5:"title";s:38:"Would you buy a house built by Toyota?";s:8:"category";s:6:"Toyota";s:2:"dc";a:1:{s:7:"creator";s:14:"Karen McGinnis";}s:7:"pubdate";s:31:"Mon, 07 Jul 2008 15:47:54 +0000";s:4:"link";s:80:"http://www.autonorth.ca/home/2008/7/7/would-you-buy-a-house-built-by-toyota.html";s:4:"guid";s:20:"75787:650998:1971723";s:11:"description";s:1102:"<p><span class="full-image-float-left"><img src="http://www.autonorth.ca/storage/ToyotaHome.jpg?__SQUARESPACE_CACHEVERSION=1215445885629" alt="ToyotaHome.jpg" title="ToyotaHome.jpg"/></span>Well let?s see, if their houses are built like their cars then heck yes.  </p>

<p>Toyota is best known for its automotive contributions like the hybrid Prius and popular Camry sedan but they?ve also been in the business of putting roofs over peoples heads.  Toyota is looking to apply its eco-friendly image and technical know-how to help boost sales of its small and little-known prefabricated-housing division.</p>

<p>Since 1975, Toyota has been building steel-frame houses designed to withstand earthquakes and typhoons and keep out burglars.  In the last year, Toyota Home, as Toyota's housing division is known, launched an aggressive advertising campaign to make more consumers aware of the brand, opened showrooms and hired architects to help redesign its line-up of homes.</p>

<p>Currently, these pre-fab. units are only available in Japan.</p>

<p>[Source: The Wall Street Journal via AutoSpies]</p>
