";s:14:"date_timestamp";i:1215445674;}i:8;a:10:{s:5:"title";s:49:"Candidates gear up to replace CAW's Buzz Hargrove";s:8:"category";s:6:"Unions";s:2:"dc";a:1:{s:7:"creator";s:14:"Karen McGinnis";}s:7:"pubdate";s:31:"Mon, 07 Jul 2008 15:27:34 +0000";s:4:"link";s:91:"http://www.autonorth.ca/home/2008/7/7/candidates-gear-up-to-replace-caws-buzz-hargrove.html";s:4:"guid";s:20:"75787:650998:1971676";s:11:"description";s:1151:"<p><span class="full-image-float-left"><img src="http://www.autonorth.ca/storage/BuzzHargrove3.jpg?__SQUARESPACE_CACHEVERSION=1215444633025" alt="BuzzHargrove3.jpg" title="BuzzHargrove3.jpg"/></span>The race is on to replace Buzz Hargrove as president of Canada's largest private-sector union.  There will be a three-way battle between two of his assistants and the president of one of the largest Canadian Auto Workers locals in the country.</p>

<p>Ken Lewenza, president of <span class="caps">CAW</span> Local 444 in Windsor, Ontario, made his entry into the campaign after winning the endorsement of the presidents of union locals in Windsor and nearby Essex and Kent counties.</p>

<p>He will join Hemi Mitic, an assistant to Mr. Hargrove who was a key negotiator in the union's breakthrough deal with auto parts giant Magna International Inc. and Tom Collins, a former head of the Canadian unit of the Retail Wholesale and Department Store Union, who said yesterday he will also throw his hat in the ring.</p>

<p>After being President of the union for 16 years, Hargrove will reach the mandatory retirement age of 65 and depart next March.</p>
";s:3:"wfw";a:1:{s:10:"commentrss";s:59:"http://www.autonorth.ca/home/rss-comments-entry-1971676.xml";}s:7:"summary";s:1151:"<p><span class="full-image-float-left"><img src="http://www.autonorth.ca/storage/BuzzHargrove3.jpg?__SQUARESPACE_CACHEVERSION=1215444633025" alt="BuzzHargrove3.jpg" title="BuzzHargrove3.jpg"/></span>The race is on to replace Buzz Hargrove as president of Canada's largest private-sector union.  There will be a three-way battle between two of his assistants and the president of one of the largest Canadian Auto Workers locals in the country.</p>

<p>Ken Lewenza, president of <span class="caps">CAW</span> Local 444 in Windsor, Ontario, made his entry into the campaign after winning the endorsement of the presidents of union locals in Windsor and nearby Essex and Kent counties.</p>

<p>He will join Hemi Mitic, an assistant to Mr. Hargrove who was a key negotiator in the union's breakthrough deal with auto parts giant Magna International Inc. and Tom Collins, a former head of the Canadian unit of the Retail Wholesale and Department Store Union, who said yesterday he will also throw his hat in the ring.</p>

<p>After being President of the union for 16 years, Hargrove will reach the mandatory retirement age of 65 and depart next March.</p>
